"""
MKT Context — Mark all 16 chapters
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/mark.json

Historical context: Mark is the earliest Gospel (ca. 65-70 CE), written for
a Roman Gentile audience during or near the Neronian persecution (64 CE)
or the Jewish War (66-70 CE). Peter is traditionally Mark's source (Papias, HE 3.39).
The suffering-discipleship theme and the Messianic Secret address a community
facing persecution who need a theology of suffering under a crucified Messiah.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p>Mark was written for a Gentile Roman audience, probably in Rome itself, during or near the Neronian persecution of 64 CE or the Jewish War of 66-70 CE. The early church tradition (Papias, apud Eusebius HE 3.39; Irenaeus, Haer. 3.1.2; Anti-Marcionite Prologue) identifies Mark as the interpreter of Peter, writing down Peter\'s preaching accurately though not in order. This social setting explains Mark\'s features: the lack of OT genealogy (less relevant for Gentiles), the explanation of Jewish customs (7:3-4, 14:12), the Latinisms in the Greek (quadrans, centurion, praetorium, legio), and the urgency of the narrative that suits a community under crisis. The word euangelion (gospel) itself is the imperial herald\'s announcement — an audacious counter-claim to Roman imperial euangelion.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Galilee was a primarily Jewish region under Herod Antipas\'s client-tetrarchy (4 BCE - 39 CE). Its population was mixed: Jewish farmers and fishermen in the interior, Hellenistic urban centers (Sepphoris, Tiberias) nearby. The fishing industry on the Sea of Galilee was a significant economic enterprise under Roman tax-contracts; the fishermen Jesus called (Simon, Andrew, James, John) were not destitute but working within a commercial fishing economy. Capernaum (1:21, Jesus\'s base of operations) was a fishing village on the northern shore of the Sea of Galilee, discovered by archaeology to have had a first-century synagogue close to where tradition locates Peter\'s house.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "13": '<p>Tax collectors (telonai) in first-century Galilee collected customs duties (tolls on goods moving through territory) rather than direct taxes. They were contracted by the Roman (or Herodian) administration and paid a fixed sum for the rights, keeping any excess they collected — a built-in incentive for overcharging that made them universally despised. Levi (Matthew) sat at a customs booth in Capernaum, likely on the major trade route from Syria to Egypt. His Aramaic name (Levi) alongside his Greek name (Matthew = gift of YHWH) suggests he was a diaspora Jew; his literacy and Greek fluency in a toll-booth role were prerequisites of the job.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "6": '<p>The Herodians were supporters of the Herodian dynasty — a politically powerful faction whose interests lay in maintaining Roman-backed Herodian rule. Their alliance with the Pharisees against Jesus (also 12:13) is an unusual coalition: the Pharisees were generally politically independent of Rome and often in tension with the Herodian dynasty (which they saw as not truly Jewish). Their shared opposition to Jesus creates the temporary alliance — the Pharisees threatened by his Torah-authority, the Herodians threatened by his popular Messianic following. Both had reason to want him eliminated before his movement grew large enough to trigger Roman reprisals against all of them.</p>'
  },
  "4": {
    "1": '<p>The Sea of Galilee (also called Lake Tiberias or Lake Kinneret) is a freshwater lake about 21 km long and 13 km wide, surrounded by hills that create sudden violent storms. Jesus\'s practice of teaching from a boat offshore (v.1) was a practical acoustics solution: the natural amphitheater of the hillside allowed many to hear with the water reducing crowd noise. The parable of the sower is agricultural common knowledge in Palestinian farming: the thin limestone-underlaid soil of Galilee produced exactly the varieties of ground described — the path between fields, rocky outcroppings, thorny areas, and the good alluvial soil in the valleys.</p>'
  },
  "5": {
    "1": '<p>The Decapolis (Ten Cities) was a league of Hellenistic cities east and southeast of the Sea of Galilee — largely Gentile territory. The presence of a large herd of pigs (v.11) confirms the Gentile setting: pig-keeping was forbidden under Levitical law and would not occur in Jewish territory. The encounter with the Gerasene demoniac (the region of the Gerasenes is probably modern Kursi on the eastern shore) is the first extended Gentile healing in Mark, foreshadowing the Gentile mission. The name Legion (v.9) is explicitly Roman: a Roman legion comprised approximately 6,000 soldiers — the demonic power takes the name of the occupying imperial force.</p>'
  },
  "6": {
    "14": '<p>Herod Antipas, tetrarch of Galilee (4 BCE - 39 CE), had divorced his Nabatean wife to marry Herodias, the wife of his half-brother Philip — a marriage John the Baptist condemned as violating Levitical law (Lev 18:16, 20:21). Josephus (Ant. 18.116-119) confirms John\'s imprisonment and execution and adds that Herod feared John\'s popular influence might lead to sedition — a political rather than personal motive. Mark\'s account emphasizes the personal vendetta of Herodias. The birthday banquet (likely at Machaerus fortress in Perea) was a Hellenistic royal celebration; the oath up to half my kingdom echoes Persian royal protocol (cf. Esth 5:3,6).</p>'
  },
  "7": {
    "1": '<p>The tradition of the elders (paradosis ton presbyteron) in Mark\'s context requires the unusual explanation in vv.3-4 that all Jews wash their hands before eating and observe other purity practices — explanation unnecessary for Jewish readers but clearly aimed at Gentile ones. The corban controversy (v.11) targets a legal device by which property could be dedicated to the temple (making it formally unavailable to others) without actually being delivered — a loophole that allowed children to evade the fifth commandment\'s financial implications toward aged parents. The Mishnah confirms corban as a legal category (m. Nedarim).</p>'
  },
  "8": {
    "27": '<p>Caesarea Philippi (modern Banias in the Golan Heights) was built by Philip the tetrarch and named for Caesar Augustus and himself. It sat at the foot of Mount Hermon near the source of the Jordan River, at the edge of Jewish territory and the beginning of Gentile Syria. A large grotto there was associated with the god Pan (the area was called Panias/Banias). The location is theologically significant: in Gentile territory, at a site dedicated to a pagan deity, Jesus receives the confession that he is the Christ — the Messianic identity is declared at the farthest geographic edge of Jewish territory, foreshadowing the Gentile mission.</p>'
  },
  "9": {
    "2": '<p>Mount Hermon (2,814 m, the highest point in the region) is the most likely site of the Transfiguration, consistent with the Caesarea Philippi location of the preceding passage and the six-day interval (9:2). The phrase they saw no one any more but Jesus only (v.8) — after Moses and Elijah depart — is the key theological statement: Moses (Torah) and Elijah (Prophets) were temporary presences who appeared to attend and then departed; Jesus alone remains. The entire OT revelation is subordinated to and surpassed by the one person whose presence is permanent and defining.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "17": '<p>The encounter with the rich young man takes place on the road to Jerusalem (v.17, 32) — the journey section that structures Mark 8:27-10:52. The term good teacher in a Jewish context was not standard address for a rabbi: Jewish teachers said good of God but not of human teachers (b. Taanit 7a). The man\'s casual use of the title prompts Jesus\'s question about its meaning. The man\'s claim to have kept all the commandments from his youth would have been heard as a standard pious claim — the rabbis debated whether perfect Torah observance was achievable in principle (it was not a scandalous claim). Jesus\'s look and love (v.21) followed by the impossible demand makes the encounter a revelation about the nature of the heart\'s attachment to possessions.</p>'
  },
  "11": {
    "15": '<p>The temple complex in Jerusalem (Herod\'s temple, begun 20 BCE, not completed until 63 CE — just 7 years before its destruction) was enormous: the Temple Mount platform covered approximately 36 acres. The Court of the Gentiles (the outermost court, open to non-Jews) was where the money-changers and animal sellers operated. The Tyrian shekel was required for the half-shekel temple tax because its silver purity was reliable; pilgrims coming from across the diaspora needed to exchange their local currency. The commerce occupied the only space designated for Gentile prayer, effectively excluding the nations from the one place in the temple complex that was theirs. Mark\'s preservation of for all nations (Isa 56:7) makes the exclusion explicit.</p>'
  },
  "12": {
    "13": '<p>The question about taxes (v.13-17) was a political trap with no safe answer in the Roman-occupied Jewish context: affirming Caesar\'s tax alienated Jewish nationalists (who considered the tax a capitulation to Roman idolatry); denying it risked arrest for sedition. The coin Jesus calls for was a denarius bearing the image and inscription of Tiberius Caesar (TIBERIUS CAESAR DIVI AUGUSTI FILIUS AUGUSTUS, with the reverse PONTIFEX MAXIMUS — high priest). For strict Jews, carrying such an idol-image was itself questionable; the fact that the Pharisees had such a coin ready reveals their own accommodation. Jesus\'s answer sidesteps the trap by distinguishing what belongs to Caesar (his coin, stamped with his image) from what belongs to God (humans, stamped with God\'s image, Gen 1:27).</p>'
  },
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>The temple complex that Jesus predicts will be destroyed (not one stone upon another, v.2) was indeed dismantled by Titus\'s forces in 70 CE; Josephus records the systematic destruction (War 6.4.5-7.1.1). The Olivet Discourse (ch.13) addresses the conflation of Jerusalem\'s destruction with the end of the age — a natural mistake given that both were expected simultaneously in Jewish eschatology. Mark\'s Olivet Discourse (briefer than Matthew\'s) reflects a community experiencing real persecution (v.9: councils, synagogues, governors, kings) consistent with the Neronian context or the Jewish War period.</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "3": '<p>The anointing at Bethany (14:3-9) takes place in the house of Simon the leper — the healed leper whose social rehabilitation Jesus performed, now hosting the messianic banquet. The woman\'s alabaster jar of nard (spikenard, <em>nardou pistikes</em>) worth more than 300 denarii (a year\'s wages for a day laborer) was the most expensive personal possession many would ever encounter. Anointing for burial was performed on the corpse after death; anointing beforehand was unprecedented. Jesus interprets her action as prophetic anointing for burial (v.8), making her the first person to act on the passion predictions he had been making since 8:31.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The Last Supper was a Passover meal (14:12-16 makes this explicit in Mark). In the first century, Passover lambs were slaughtered at the temple on Nisan 14 (beginning of the Day of Preparation); the Passover meal was eaten that night (Nisan 15). The meal included the Passover lamb, bitter herbs, unleavened bread, and the Hallel Psalms (113-118). Jesus reinterprets the bread and the cup within this Passover framework — the cup of wine (probably the third of four traditional Passover cups, the cup of redemption) becomes the cup of the new covenant in his blood. The meal is simultaneously Passover-completion (the old Exodus) and Passover-inauguration (the new Exodus).</p>'
  },
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>The Roman trial before Pilate involves several historically verifiable elements: the prefect\'s role in capital cases (Jewish courts could not execute without Roman authorization, John 18:31 — confirmed by Josephus and Roman provincial law), the custom of releasing a prisoner at the feast (a paschal amnesty practice known from papyrological evidence and Josephus Ant. 20.215 for analogous pardons), and the location of the praetorium in Jerusalem (either the Antonia Fortress or Herod\'s Palace in the upper city). The crowd\'s choice of Barabbas (whose name means son of the father, bar Abba) over Jesus is one of the Gospel\'s stark ironies: they release the son of the father and condemn the Son of the Father.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "1": '<p>Mark\'s original ending at 16:8 (they said nothing to anyone, for they were afraid) is among the most discussed textual questions in NT scholarship. The longer ending (16:9-20) is absent from the oldest manuscripts (Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) and contains vocabulary and style not found in Mark 1-15. The shorter ending is attested by Eusebius and Jerome as the best manuscript tradition. The abrupt ending at 16:8 may be deliberate: Mark\'s Gospel begins with abrupt urgency and ends with the open invitation of an unanswered question. The resurrection is announced but not narratively resolved — the reader is placed in the position of the women: what will you do with the empty tomb and the promise that the risen Lord goes before you?</p>'
  }
}

FILL_CH3_4 = {
"3": {
"1": "<p>The synagogue served as the community center of every Jewish town&mdash;a place for Torah reading, prayer, legal dispute, and teaching. Attendance on the Sabbath was expected of all adult Jewish men. Jesus consistently teaches <em>in</em> synagogues rather than outside them, marking him as a recognized teacher operating within established Jewish institutional space.</p>",
"2": "<p>Jewish oral law (later codified in the Mishnah tractate <em>Shabbat</em>) categorized thirty-nine primary categories of prohibited Sabbath labor, including reaping, threshing, and binding. Healing was permitted only when life was in immediate danger (<em>pikuach nefesh</em>). A shriveled hand posed no mortal threat, so treating it on the Sabbath was halakhically controversial. The watchers are not curious bystanders&mdash;they are building a legal case.</p>",
"3": "<p>Jesus commands the man to stand in the center of the assembly. This is a deliberate public act: rather than healing quietly, Jesus stages the confrontation. In synagogue culture, standing before the congregation while the community watches carries both dignity and vulnerability. Jesus makes his critics witness the moment of decision.</p>",
"4": "<p>The question Jesus poses is a classic rabbinic <em>kal va-homer</em> argument: if something greater is permitted, something lesser surely is. He reframes the Sabbath debate not as labor-category law but as moral imperative&mdash;is Sabbath a day for life or for abandonment? His opponents cannot answer without either condemning their own logic or conceding his point. Their silence is not ignorance; it is refusal.</p>",
"5": "<p>The phrase &ldquo;hardness of heart&rdquo; (<em>porosis tes kardias</em>) echoes Hebrew <em>qeshi lev</em>, a scriptural idiom for willful refusal of divine instruction found in Exodus (Pharaoh), Ezekiel, and the Psalms. It describes not emotional coldness but deliberate moral resistance. Mark&rsquo;s note that Jesus felt both anger and grief simultaneously is psychologically precise&mdash;righteous anger and compassionate sorrow as co-present responses to injustice.</p>",
"7": "<p>The Sea of Galilee (Lake Kinneret) was the commercial and social artery of Galilee. Its western shore hosted major fishing towns like Capernaum, Bethsaida, and Magdala. Jesus&rsquo; withdrawal to the lakeside rather than staying in the synagogue town reflects a pattern of movement away from centers of formal religious authority toward open, liminal spaces accessible to larger crowds.</p>",
"8": "<p>The geographic list&mdash;Galilee, Judea, Jerusalem, Idumea, Transjordan, Tyre, and Sidon&mdash;covers the full compass of historic Israel plus neighboring territories. Idumea (Edomite land south of Judah) was forcibly converted to Judaism under the Hasmonean king John Hyrcanus in the second century BCE. The inclusion of Tyre and Sidon (Phoenician coastal cities) signals that Jesus&rsquo; reputation has crossed ethnic and regional boundaries.</p>",
"9": "<p>The small boat (<em>ploiarion</em>) was likely a standard Galilean fishing vessel capable of holding several people. Using the boat as a floating platform kept Jesus from being crushed by the crowd pressing forward. The Sea of Galilee&rsquo;s natural amphitheater-like shoreline also made lakeside teaching acoustically effective for large gatherings.</p>",
"10": "<p>Touch was understood in the ancient Mediterranean world as a powerful medium of transmission&mdash;of both uncleanness and holiness. The Levitical purity system taught that certain conditions (skin disease, discharge, death) transferred ritual impurity by contact. The crowd&rsquo;s pressing forward to touch Jesus reverses this logic: rather than their need contaminating him, his power flows outward to them. This tactile healing dynamic recurs throughout Mark.</p>",
"11": "<p>Falling prostrate (<em>prospipto</em>) before a figure of authority was a common act of submission or petition in Hellenistic and Jewish contexts. That the impure spirits perform this act of obeisance while simultaneously being silenced highlights the irony Mark enjoys: the supernatural world recognizes Jesus&rsquo; identity while the human religious establishment denies it.</p>",
"12": "<p>Scholars call this pattern in Mark the &ldquo;messianic secret.&rdquo; First-century Jewish messianic expectations were intensely political&mdash;many anticipated a military liberator who would expel Rome and restore Davidic sovereignty. A premature public identification of Jesus as Messiah risked inflaming these expectations in ways that would derail his actual mission. Silencing the spirits prevents a distorted announcement.</p>",
"13": "<p>Mountains in the Hebrew scriptures are covenant sites: Sinai (Torah given), Moriah (Abraham&rsquo;s binding of Isaac), Horeb (Elijah&rsquo;s encounter with God), Zion (the temple). When Jesus goes up a mountain and calls disciples to him, he acts within this tradition of divine summons at elevated holy ground. The sovereign phrasing &ldquo;those he wanted&rdquo; echoes the language of divine election throughout the Hebrew Bible.</p>",
"14": "<p>Appointing twelve carries unmistakable symbolic weight in a Jewish context: twelve tribes of Israel, twelve patriarchs, twelve loaves of showbread. The number signals that Jesus is reconstituting or fulfilling Israel, not merely forming a religious club. The Greek <em>apostolos</em> means one sent with delegated authority&mdash;an official emissary who represents the sender&rsquo;s person and message.</p>",
"15": "<p>Exorcism authority was understood in first-century Judaism as a demonstration of divine power over the spiritual forces of disorder. Exorcists existed in Jewish practice (Josephus; Acts 19:13), but their methods typically involved elaborate rituals and invocations of divine names. Jesus exorcises by direct command, which struck observers as an extraordinary claim of personal authority over the spirit world.</p>",
"16": "<p>Renaming is a covenant act in the Hebrew Bible: Abram becomes Abraham, Jacob becomes Israel. When Jesus renames Simon as Peter (<em>Petros</em>/Kepha, meaning rock), he performs a symbolic act of new identity conferral. The Aramaic <em>Kepha</em> (Cephas) was the name in use among Aramaic-speaking communities; the Greek <em>Petros</em> is Mark&rsquo;s rendering for his audience.</p>",
"17": "<p>Boanerges is a Semitic term that Mark transliterates and then translates for his Greek-speaking audience. Aramaic <em>bene regesh</em> or a related form means &ldquo;sons of tumult/thunder.&rdquo; Mark&rsquo;s practice of providing Aramaic terms with translations (also <em>talitha koum</em>, <em>ephphatha</em>, <em>Eloi Eloi lama sabachthani</em>) is distinctive among the Gospels and suggests a tradition rooted in bilingual Palestinian communities.</p>",
"18": "<p>Simon &ldquo;the Zealot&rdquo; (<em>ho Kananaios</em> in some manuscripts, from Aramaic <em>qan&rsquo;an</em>) was associated with a movement of intensely nationalistic Jews who resisted Roman taxation and occupation. The Zealot party as a formal group crystallized more sharply in the Jewish War (66&ndash;70 CE), but the ideological tendency was present earlier. The list includes a tax collector (Levi/Matthew) and a Zealot&mdash;normally bitter political enemies&mdash;within the same twelve.</p>",
"19": "<p>Judas Iscariot&rsquo;s surname is debated. The most common interpretation is <em>Ish-Kerioth</em> = man from Kerioth, a town in Judea, which would make him the only non-Galilean of the Twelve. An alternative reading links the name to <em>sicarius</em> (Latin dagger-man), referring to a type of urban assassin active in first-century Judea. Mark&rsquo;s stark gloss &ldquo;who betrayed him&rdquo; casts a shadow over the list from its first mention.</p>",
"20": "<p>The house (<em>oikos</em>) in Galilean village culture was a multi-generational compound, not a private residence. Hospitality obligations were strong: a house where a teacher of Jesus&rsquo; reputation held court would attract visitors continuously. The detail that Jesus and his disciples could not even eat indicates the extraordinary press of demand, and sets up the family intervention that follows.</p>",
"21": "<p>The phrase <em>hoi par&rsquo; autou</em> (those with him / his own people) likely refers to family members. In an honor-shame culture, a family member who attracted crowds by unusual behavior risked bringing shame on the entire household. To call someone &ldquo;out of his mind&rdquo; (<em>exeste</em>) was to make a socially protective move&mdash;distancing the family from responsibility for his actions and attempting to regain social control by removing him from public view.</p>",
"22": "<p>The scribes who come down from Jerusalem are not local critics but an official delegation. Their charge involves Beelzebul, a name with complex background: <em>Baal Zebub</em> (lord of the flies) appears in 2 Kings 1 as a Philistine deity mocked by its name; <em>Baal Zebul</em> (lord of the dwelling / exalted lord) may have been the Canaanite name. By the Second Temple period, Beelzebul had become a name for the chief of demons. The charge is not simple insult but a formal accusation of sorcery&mdash;a capital offense under Torah.</p>",
"23": "<p>The <em>mashal</em> (parable, riddle, comparison) was one of the most versatile forms of Jewish wisdom discourse, used in Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, and extensively in later rabbinic literature. A mashal typically poses an analogy or scenario that requires interpretive work from the audience. Jesus uses the form to engage his accusers on their own terms, forcing them to reason through the internal coherence of their own charge.</p>",
"24": "<p>The divided-kingdom image would have immediate resonance in a region that had experienced exactly that: the kingdom of Israel split into northern and southern kingdoms after Solomon, and both eventually fell to foreign powers. Roman-occupied Galilee remembered that internal division had been a cause of past national catastrophe. Jesus&rsquo; argument is both logical and politically loaded.</p>",
"25": "<p>The <em>oikos</em> (house/household) was the basic unit of ancient Mediterranean social and economic life&mdash;not just a building but a kinship network with shared resources, reputation, and obligations. A house divided against itself risked economic collapse and social disgrace. The image would strike any village listener as a vivid and obvious truth about communal survival.</p>",
"26": "<p>The reductio ad absurdum: if Jesus casts out demons by demonic power, then Satan is attacking his own forces, which means Satan&rsquo;s kingdom is already collapsing. The argument grants the premises of the accusation and shows they lead to the accuser&rsquo;s conclusion being self-defeating. Ancient audiences familiar with logical argument forms would recognize this as a decisive rhetorical move.</p>",
"27": "<p>The strong man parable draws on a common scenario from everyday life: before robbing a well-guarded house, you must first overpower the guard. In Greek and Roman literature, binding enemies before plundering them was a standard military image. Jesus presents himself implicitly as the one who has already entered the strong man&rsquo;s domain and bound him&mdash;explaining why exorcisms are possible at all.</p>",
"28": "<p>The solemn &ldquo;Amen I say to you&rdquo; formula (<em>Amen lego hymin</em>) is distinctive to Jesus in the gospel tradition&mdash;Jewish teachers typically said &ldquo;Thus says the LORD&rdquo; when delivering authoritative teaching; Jesus speaks on his own authority. The breadth of forgiveness promised is extraordinary: all sins, all blasphemies of human speech. This makes the exception in v29 all the more severe by contrast.</p>",
"29": "<p>The concept of an unforgivable sin had some precedent in Jewish thought: Yom Kippur atonement was understood to cover most transgressions, but certain grave sins (particularly those committed with a &ldquo;high hand,&rdquo; i.e., deliberate defiance) were not automatically covered. The scribes&rsquo; identification of the Holy Spirit&rsquo;s work as demonic is precisely the kind of willful inversion of moral reality that places a person outside the possibility of repentance.</p>",
"30": "<p>Mark&rsquo;s editorial explanation links the unforgivable sin teaching directly back to the Jerusalem scribes&rsquo; accusation in v22. This is a narrative anchor that prevents readers from universalizing the saying abstractly: in its original context it addresses a specific act of deliberate malicious misattribution by religious experts who had full knowledge of what they were doing.</p>",
"31": "<p>Jesus&rsquo; mother and brothers standing outside while he is surrounded inside creates a visual tableau of inside/outside that Mark develops through ch 4 (insiders who understand vs. outsiders who do not). Family&rsquo;s arrival at this moment, especially given their earlier evaluation in v21, creates dramatic tension: will Jesus grant them insider access on the basis of blood alone?</p>",
"32": "<p>The crowd serves as an intermediary between the outside family and Jesus inside. In ancient Palestinian culture, access to important figures was mediated through intermediaries and gatekeepers. The crowd&rsquo;s message is a social obligation claim: your family is here, come out. Jesus&rsquo; response redefines what family obligation means in the new community he is forming.</p>",
"33": "<p>Answering a question with a counter-question is a characteristic rabbinic teaching technique. It forces the listeners to examine their own assumptions and draws them into the reasoning process. The question &ldquo;Who are my mother and my brothers?&rdquo; is not a denial of family but an invitation to reconsider the basis of the relationship.</p>",
"34": "<p>The visual detail of Jesus looking around in a circle (<em>periblepsas</em>) at those seated around him is one of Mark&rsquo;s characteristic observational notes&mdash;he uses this verb multiple times to capture Jesus surveying a situation. The seated posture of the inner group contrasts with the standing family outside, reinforcing the spatial symbolism of insiders and outsiders.</p>",
"35": "<p>Defining family by doing God&rsquo;s will rather than blood kinship draws on deep threads in the Hebrew Bible: Ruth&rsquo;s loyalty defined her as more truly family than biological connection; the prophetic tradition spoke of a renewed covenant community bound by obedience to Torah. In an honor-shame culture where family identity was near-absolute, this redefinition was socially radical. Jesus is not dismissing his mother; he is expanding the category of belonging.</p>"
},
"4": {
"2": "<p>The <em>mashal</em> tradition in Jewish pedagogy used analogy, riddle, and comparison to convey wisdom that could not be transmitted by straightforward proposition. Proverbs is structured around such wisdom forms; later rabbinic literature (<em>midrash</em>) deployed parables extensively to interpret Torah. Mark notes that Jesus taught &ldquo;many things&rdquo; in parables&mdash;suggesting this was his primary teaching mode, not an occasional device.</p>",
"3": "<p>The imperative &ldquo;Listen!&rdquo; (<em>Akouete</em>) echoes the Shema: &ldquo;Hear (<em>Shema</em>), O Israel.&rdquo; The call to active hearing frames the parable as more than illustration&mdash;it is a summons requiring the same kind of covenantal attentiveness that Deuteronomy demanded. The parable&rsquo;s subject (seed and soil) belongs to the world every Galilean peasant farmer inhabited daily.</p>",
"4": "<p>First-century Palestinian farming broadcast seed widely across unplowed or partially cleared ground before (or after) plowing, rather than planting in prepared rows. A field&rsquo;s edges typically included footpaths used by workers and passersby, making some seed inevitably land on compacted, birdwatched ground. The scenario is agricultural realism, not carelessness on the farmer&rsquo;s part.</p>",
"5": "<p>Much of the Galilean and Judean hill country consists of thin topsoil over limestone bedrock&mdash;it appears fertile and seeds sprout quickly because the rock retains warmth, but roots cannot penetrate deep enough to find moisture during the dry season (April&ndash;October). Anyone farming in this terrain would immediately recognize the image.</p>",
"6": "<p>The Palestinian growing season means young plants face scorching heat and complete drought after the spring rains stop. Shallow-rooted plants that sprouted quickly on rocky ground lack the moisture reserves to survive. The agricultural logic is straightforward to any Galilean farmer: fast growth without root depth is not a sign of health but a portent of failure.</p>",
"7": "<p>Thorny weeds compete aggressively with grain for soil nutrients and moisture in the ancient Near East. Thistles and thorns were understood as part of the cursed ground of Genesis 3:18. A plot that looks cleared may still harbor root systems of thorny plants that re-emerge and choke productive crops. The farmer&rsquo;s inability to fully eliminate thorns was a familiar frustration.</p>",
"8": "<p>A tenfold yield was considered a good harvest in ancient Mediterranean agriculture; thirtyfold was excellent; sixtyfold and a hundredfold were extraordinary. Genesis 26:12 records Isaac reaping a hundredfold as a sign of divine blessing. The parable&rsquo;s closing yield figures are not average expectations but images of abundance that signal something beyond ordinary agricultural outcomes.</p>",
"9": "<p>&ldquo;Whoever has ears to hear, let them hear&rdquo; is a wisdom refrain found in prophetic and apocalyptic literature calling for active interpretive engagement. Hearing in the Hebraic sense (<em>shama</em>) means not just acoustic reception but attentive response&mdash;the same word covers both hearing and obeying. The refrain marks the parable&rsquo;s end and signals that its meaning is not self-evident but requires willing discernment.</p>",
"10": "<p>Private instruction to an inner circle of disciples was a recognized practice among Jewish teachers. The distinction between public teaching in parables and private explanation to those already committed reflects a rabbinic pattern of graduated disclosure: foundational wisdom was accessible to all, while deeper interpretive keys were entrusted to students who had proven their commitment. The Twelve plus &ldquo;those around him&rdquo; constitute this inner group.</p>",
"11": "<p>The word <em>musterion</em> (mystery) carries technical weight from Jewish apocalyptic literature. In Daniel 2 (Aramaic <em>r&acirc;z</em>), it refers to divine secrets revealed to chosen recipients about the hidden plan of history. The Dead Sea Scrolls community used similar language about divine secrets given to the community&rsquo;s insiders. Jesus is using the language of apocalyptic disclosure: the kingdom&rsquo;s arrival is a revealed secret, not an observable political event.</p>",
"12": "<p>Isaiah 6:9&ndash;10 occurs in the context of Isaiah&rsquo;s commission: God sends him to preach to a people whose hearts are already hard. The prophet&rsquo;s message will paradoxically deepen the hardening already underway, so that judgment runs its course and only a remnant remains. Jesus&rsquo; citation locates his parabolic teaching within the same prophetic pattern: the word of the kingdom both reveals (to those with soft hearts) and conceals (from those already closed), making the parables a moment of judgment as well as invitation.</p>",
"13": "<p>The rebuke &ldquo;Do you not understand this parable?&rdquo; implies that the sower parable is foundational&mdash;it is about how parables themselves work, how the word is received or resisted. If the disciples cannot decode this one, they lack the interpretive framework for everything else Jesus will say in parabolic form. The question is a teaching provocation, not a dismissal.</p>",
"14": "<p>Identifying the seed as &ldquo;the word&rdquo; (<em>ho logos</em>) draws on the Hebrew concept of <em>davar</em>&mdash;the divine word that accomplishes what God sends it to do (Isaiah 55:10&ndash;11). Preaching is seed-scattering: the teacher cannot control the soil, only cast the seed. The image both honors the teacher&rsquo;s role and relativizes it&mdash;outcomes depend on the receptiveness of hearers, not just the skill of the sower.</p>",
"15": "<p>In apocalyptic Jewish thought, Satan and his agents were understood to actively work against the reception of divine revelation. The bird that snatches seed from the path maps onto this cosmic resistance. This verse interprets not failed teaching but active spiritual opposition as the explanation for why some hearers remain entirely unreceptive despite outward hearing.</p>",
"16": "<p>The rocky-ground hearer receives the word &ldquo;with joy&rdquo; (<em>meta charas</em>)&mdash;enthusiastic, immediate positive response. But rootedness, not initial enthusiasm, is the mark of genuine reception. Tribulation (<em>thlipsis</em>) and persecution (<em>diogmos</em>) are standard vocabulary in Jewish and early Christian texts for the suffering that accompanies faithful witness. The rocky-ground hearer has no reservoir of conviction to sustain them when opposition comes.</p>",
"17": "<p>The connection between rootedness and endurance under trial reflects a wisdom tradition found in Psalms and Proverbs: the righteous person is like a tree planted by water (Psalm 1:3), whose roots sustain it in drought. Shallow reception that cannot survive pressure is diagnosed with pastoral precision&mdash;the problem is the absence of root, not moral failure per se.</p>",
"18": "<p>The thorny-ground hearer hears the word but allows it to be crowded out. The phrase &ldquo;cares of this age&rdquo; (<em>hai merimnai tou aionos</em>) uses apocalyptic temporal language: &ldquo;this age&rdquo; stands in contrast to &ldquo;the age to come.&rdquo; Anxious preoccupation with present-age concerns (economics, security, status) prevents the word from bearing fruit without requiring outright rejection.</p>",
"19": "<p>The three competing elements&mdash;worldly anxiety, wealth, and desire for other things&mdash;reflect concerns that appear prominently in Jewish wisdom literature as obstacles to Torah fidelity. Proverbs and Sirach repeatedly warn that wealth and its pursuit can displace wisdom. The word &ldquo;choke&rdquo; (<em>sympnigo</em>) is vivid agricultural imagery: the word-plant is not killed outright but slowly strangled by competing growth.</p>",
"20": "<p>The good-soil hearer hears, accepts, and produces fruit in graduated quantities (thirty, sixty, a hundred). The verb &ldquo;accept&rdquo; (<em>paradechontai</em>) implies active reception and welcoming, not just passive hearing. The graduated yields suggest varied levels of fruitfulness within genuine receptiveness&mdash;not a single ideal but a spectrum of faithful response.</p>",
"21": "<p>A household oil lamp (<em>luchnos</em>) burned olive oil and provided a modest but essential light in single-room stone houses. The lampstand (<em>luchnia</em>) positioned the lamp where its light could reach the whole room. No one would light a lamp and then obscure it under a grain measure or put it under a bed where it would be useless. The image argues from the absurdity of concealment: lamps are made to illumine, not to hide.</p>",
"22": "<p>The saying &ldquo;whatever is hidden is meant to be disclosed&rdquo; fits the apocalyptic pattern of temporary concealment followed by revelation. In Jewish apocalyptic thought (Daniel, 1 Enoch), divine secrets are sealed for a time and then unveiled at the appointed moment. The parables&rsquo; cryptic quality is not permanent esotericism but temporary: what is veiled now will be made fully manifest.</p>",
"23": "<p>The second occurrence of the hearing refrain (cf. v9) creates a formal bracket around the inner teaching material. In ancient oral composition, such repeated formulas marked structural units and signaled to listeners that a section was concluding. Mark preserves this oral-pedagogical rhythm, which suggests these teachings circulated first in spoken form before being written down.</p>",
"24": "<p>The measure-for-measure principle was deeply embedded in Jewish legal and wisdom thinking: God repays according to one&rsquo;s own standard of dealing. The same principle appears in rabbinic texts (&ldquo;With the measure a man measures, he is measured&rdquo;). Applied here to hearing: those who invest attentive effort in receiving the word receive proportionally greater understanding in return.</p>",
"25": "<p>The paradoxical saying about having and not-having reflects an economic reality familiar to Palestinian villagers: those with resources can grow them, while those without resources lose even what little they have. Jesus applies this economic logic to spiritual receptiveness&mdash;engagement with the word builds capacity for more engagement, while non-engagement atrophies even initial understanding. Similar sayings appear in rabbinic literature (<em>Avot</em>).</p>",
"26": "<p>The parable of the seed growing secretly appears only in Mark among the four Gospels. The key observation is <em>automate</em> (by itself, automatically): the earth produces grain through a process the farmer did not design and cannot manage. The kingdom&rsquo;s growth is not dependent on human effort or understanding.</p>",
"27": "<p>The daily rhythm of sleep and waking, night and day, contrasts with the farmer&rsquo;s ignorance of how the seed germinates. Ancient farmers knew the stages of growth from observation but not their mechanism. The parable&rsquo;s point is not agricultural instruction but the independence of the kingdom&rsquo;s growth from human management or comprehension&mdash;God&rsquo;s purposes advance even when his servants are asleep.</p>",
"28": "<p>The three-stage sequence&mdash;blade (<em>chortos</em>), ear (<em>stachus</em>), full grain (<em>pleres sitos</em>)&mdash;describes the grain growing season that every Galilean listener observed annually from winter planting through spring harvest. The precision of the observation grounds the parable in lived agricultural experience. Growth follows its own ordained sequence; the farmer does not cause it but learns to read its stages.</p>",
"29": "<p>The harvest image draws directly on Joel 3:13: &ldquo;Swing the sickle, for the harvest is ripe.&rdquo; In the Hebrew prophets, harvest was a standard image for eschatological judgment&mdash;the time when God&rsquo;s purposes come to completion and accounts are settled. The farmer who was passive during growth becomes active at harvest. The kingdom that grew secretly will be gathered publicly.</p>",
"30": "<p>The double question (&ldquo;What shall we say&hellip; or what parable shall we use?&rdquo;) is itself a kind of mashal-within-mashal&mdash;Jesus openly deliberates about which comparison best captures his subject. This meta-rhetorical move invites listeners into the comparison-making process. The second question implies that any single comparison will be inadequate; the kingdom exceeds available analogies.</p>",
"31": "<p>In first-century Jewish proverbial speech, the mustard seed was the standard example of the smallest measurable quantity&mdash;&ldquo;a matter as small as a mustard seed&rdquo; was a common idiom in rabbinic literature. The contrast between the proverbially smallest seed and a substantial plant would have been immediately legible. The kingdom&rsquo;s origins are similarly inauspicious by any human standard of measurement.</p>",
"32": "<p>The image of birds nesting in the branches of a great tree echoes Ezekiel 17:23 (where a cedar represents the restored Davidic kingdom) and Daniel 4:12 (the world-tree of Nebuchadnezzar&rsquo;s vision). In both texts, the nesting birds represent the nations finding shelter and provision. Jesus&rsquo; allusion suggests the mustard-seed kingdom will ultimately shelter peoples beyond Israel&mdash;a quiet but significant claim about the kingdom&rsquo;s scope.</p>",
"33": "<p>The phrase &ldquo;as much as they could understand&rdquo; (<em>kathos edynanto akouein</em>) reflects a pastoral and pedagogical principle: instruction is calibrated to the capacity of the learner. This is not condescension but gradualism&mdash;the same wisdom tradition that produced Proverbs&rsquo; graduated instruction from simple observations to complex reflection. The crowds receive what they can bear; more is reserved for those ready to receive it.</p>",
"34": "<p>Mark&rsquo;s note that Jesus explained everything privately to his disciples creates a two-tier teaching structure: public parabolic speech for the crowd, private interpretive access for the inner circle. This pattern resembles the Qumran community&rsquo;s distinction between public teaching and esoteric interpretations reserved for the initiated, and Jewish apocalyptic writings that seal mysteries for a chosen remnant. The disciples are given hermeneutical keys, not just facts.</p>",
"35": "<p>The &ldquo;other side&rdquo; of the Sea of Galilee was predominantly Gentile territory&mdash;the Decapolis region, a league of Hellenistic cities east of the Jordan. Crossing to the other side in Mark consistently marks transitions into Gentile space. The disciples&rsquo; encounter with Jesus&rsquo; power during the storm becomes preparation for ministry beyond Jewish borders. Evening crossings on the lake were common for fishermen familiar with its waters and winds.</p>",
"36": "<p>The detail that they took Jesus &ldquo;just as he was&rdquo; means he was already in the boat used for teaching (see v1)&mdash;no preparation, no ritual transition. The presence of &ldquo;other boats&rdquo; alongside them is a realistic nautical detail that also hints at a wider community of followers beyond the Twelve who accompanied the crossing.</p>",
"37": "<p>The Sea of Galilee is approximately 700 feet below sea level and surrounded by hills with gaps that channel cold air from the north. When cooler air descends rapidly through these topographic corridors into the warm lake basin, sudden violent squalls (<em>lailaps</em>) can arise with little warning, creating waves capable of swamping small vessels. Galilean fishermen knew this risk intimately.</p>",
"38": "<p>The stern (<em>prymna</em>) was the aft section of the boat, where a cushion (<em>proskephalaion</em>) would have been placed for the helmsman or a passenger. Jesus asleep on a cushion during a violent storm is a precise nautical detail unusual enough in its specificity to suggest eyewitness recollection. The disciples&rsquo; address &ldquo;Teacher, don&rsquo;t you care?&rdquo; is an accusation of indifference, born of panic.</p>",
"39": "<p>The verb used for rebuking the wind (<em>epetimesen</em>) is the same verb Mark uses for Jesus rebuking demons (1:25). In ancient cosmology, chaotic sea and storm were associated with hostile cosmic forces&mdash;not merely weather but the powers of disorder. The Hebrew Bible repeatedly describes God subduing the sea at creation and in the Exodus. Jesus&rsquo; rebuke of the storm uses the vocabulary of exorcism applied to the natural world.</p>",
"40": "<p>The pairing of fear and faith reflects a pattern throughout the Hebrew wisdom and prophetic tradition: fear of God is the beginning of wisdom, while fear of circumstances signals misplaced trust. The disciples&rsquo; fear of the storm is not criticized as cowardice but as a failure to understand who is in the boat with them. The question &ldquo;Do you still have no faith?&rdquo; is diagnostic rather than condemnatory.</p>",
"41": "<p>The disciples&rsquo; concluding question&mdash;&ldquo;Who is this?&rdquo;&mdash;echoes Psalm 89:9 (&ldquo;You rule the raging sea; when its waves mount up, you still them&rdquo;) and Psalm 107:28&ndash;29 (&ldquo;He made the storm be still, and the waves of the sea were hushed&rdquo;). In the Hebrew Bible, authority over the sea belongs to God alone. The question is therefore not curiosity about a human teacher but confrontation with an identity that exceeds all human categories.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'mark')
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH3_4)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'mark', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Mark mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
